<div id="banking" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">01</span>The banking model of education</h2>
  <p>The dominant model of education treats students as empty containers to be filled with knowledge deposited by teachers. Students receive, memorize, and repeat. The world is presented as fixed, given, static — something to be described and adapted to, not questioned or transformed.</p>
  <p>Freire called this the banking model. Its effect is not just ignorance — it is a particular kind of subjectivity: the passive recipient who accepts their condition as natural, who sees the world as something that happens to them rather than something they participate in making.</p>
</div>
<div id="conscientization" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">02</span>Conscientization</h2>
  <p>Working with illiterate peasants in northeast Brazil, Freire developed a different approach. Instead of teaching people to read and then providing content, he started from the words and situations that were already meaningful in their lives — words like "land," "work," "rent." In discussing those words, people began to analyze the conditions of their existence: not just naming the world, but questioning it.</p>
  <p>He called this process conscientization — the development of critical consciousness. It's not just gaining information. It's coming to see your situation as historical and changeable rather than natural and fixed. Coming to see yourself as a subject — someone who acts — rather than an object — something acted upon.</p>
  <div class="callout"><span class="callout-label">The key move</span><p>Literacy is not primarily about decoding letters. It is about reading the world — understanding the conditions of your life well enough to act on them. The two are connected: learning to read words is part of learning to read power.</p></div>
</div>
<div id="dialogue" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">03</span>Dialogue as method</h2>
  <p>If the banking model deposits knowledge from above, the alternative is dialogue — a relationship in which both teacher and student are simultaneously learners. Not because all knowledge is equally valid, but because the process of critical thinking requires genuine encounter: the teacher brings knowledge, the student brings experience, and meaning is made in the exchange between them.</p>
  <p>Freire was clear that dialogue doesn't mean anything goes. It requires humility, trust, hope, and critical thinking. It's incompatible with arrogance, manipulation, and the assumption that the teacher already has the answers the student needs to receive.</p>
</div>
<div id="commons" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">04</span>Why this matters for the commons</h2>
  <p>Building commons-based institutions requires not just different rules but different people — people who understand themselves as capable of collective governance, who have practiced the skills of democratic deliberation, who can analyze power and act on that analysis. This is what Freire's pedagogy is for.</p>
  <p>Every commons needs a process of conscientization — a way of helping participants understand the conditions they're working in, the forces acting on them, the history of how they got there. Without that, even well-designed institutions drift back toward hierarchy, because the participants don't have the consciousness to maintain alternatives.</p>
</div>
